column1: ## Variant can be interpreted by following the columns from left to right.
## This classification scheme was implemented in Java, and used to
## benchmark GAVIN in the paper (Van der Velde et al., using r0.2), see:
## Explanation of the gene calibration categories:
## C3 = CADD may be predictive (pval > 0.05 but with few samples)
## C4 = CADD not so predictive (pval > 0.05 with enough samples)
## C5 = CADD not so predictive (population CADD > pathogenic CADD)
## I1 = HIGH impact unique for pathogenic variants
## I2 = MODERATE or HIGH impact unique for pathogenic variants
## I3 = LOW or MODERATE or HIGH impact unique for pathogenic variants
## T1 = Too few exac variants after filtering with pathogenic 95th percentile MAF.
## T2 = Too few exac variants after filtering with impact distribution.
## N1 = Too few ClinVar variants for calibration at this time.
## N2 = Too few ExAC variants found for calibration.
## For C1 and C2, we use CADD score means of stratified benign and pathogenic variants.
## For C3, C4 and C5 we use 95th percentile sensitivity/specificity thresholds of benign and pathogenic CADD score distributions.
## Genome-wide rules are applied if the gene-specific rules have failed to classify.
## These general rules are as follows:
## If variant MAF greater than 0.004264361 -> benign
